;
;
;PAWN SHOP
NUMBER 1936
NAME The Pawn Shop
CHANNEL 777
REGION 1
CAFE
MOVEMENT_ASTRAL
INDOOR_FLOOR
FIXED_LIGHT

CALL 49

EXIT O 1945

ITEM 0 1677 ADJ1=154 ADJ2=806
ITEM 1 420 ADJ1=347
EXTEND 1 that could use more than a little scrubbing
PUT 1 512
ITEM 2 249
ITEM 3 720 ADJ1=415 ADJ2=355
ITEM 4 204 ADJ1=529
EXTEND 4 mounted on the cash register

*DESCRIPTION_START
This small pawn shop is a bit run down, its hardwood floor in need of a good
polish and the walls, you suspect, should be a bit brighter than their current
shade of off-white. A large picture window provides a spectacular view of the
boardwalk and the ocean below. An elderly man stands behind the worn counter,
looking both unfriendly and quite bored. A small paper sign is taped to the
side of the cash register.
*DESCRIPTION_END

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 0
The floor shows every scrape, every scuffle, every booted footfall ever made
in the shop as clearly as prints on snow-covered ground. Your shoes stick ever
so slightly to it, you notice, as though more than a little dirt has made its
permanent home in the cracks and grooves of the weathered planks.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB KICK 0
 CLEARVERB
 ECHO PLAYER You stamp your foot on the floor. Ick, it's... sticky.
 ECHO OTHERS %N stamps %h foot on the floor.
ENDIF

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 1
You suspect that these four walls have never seen a damp cloth or duster, so
thickly layered are they with trails of gray dust. The owners appear to have
simply slapped on coat after coat of paint whenever it looked too dirty,
resulting in a number of cracked and peeling locations where trapped air has
bubbled to the surface.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFTOUCH 1
 CLEARVERB
 ECHO PLAYER You touch the wall, getting a thick, fuzzy layer of dust all over your hand.
 ECHO OTHERS %N touches the wall, %h hand coming away half-covered with dust.
ENDIF

IFPREVERB LOOK 2
   CLEARVERB
   AFFECT 1903
   EQUAL FLAG4 PLRSINROOM
   AFFECT 1924
   IFVAR FLAG4 = 0
      ECHO PLAYER You look out onto the boardwalk, noting that the white railings look brighter
      ECHO PLAYER than the walls in here even when seen through the dusty glass.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR FLAG4 = 1
      ECHO PLAYER You look out onto the boardwalk, noting that the white railings look brighter
      ECHO PLAYER than the walls in here even when seen through the dusty glass. A lone figure
      ECHO PLAYER stands outside, not looking in your direction.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR FLAG4 > 1
      STRCVT 0 FLAG4
      ECHO PLAYER You look out onto the boardwalk, noting that the white railings look brighter
      ECHO PLAYER than the walls in here even when seen through the dusty glass. %0 people are
      ECHO PLAYER standing out there, looking at the sea.
   ENDIF
ENDIF

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 3
The counter has seen better days. From the look of it, actually, every day
before this one was a better day... and every day after it will be worse. The
deterioration present is quite impressive, really. A loose nail hanging ready
to rip a passing shirt here, splinters lying in ambush for the unwary palm
there. A cash register sits atop it, as battered and decrepit as the counter, a
Small paper sign mounted on its side.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFVERB THUMP 3
   ECHO ALL The old man behind the counter looks up and says, "Yeah, yeah, be right with you."
ENDIF

IFPREVERB KICK 3
   CLEARVERB
   IFVAR ROUNDTIME ! 0
      STRCVT 0 ROUNDTIME
      ECHO PLAYER [Wait %0 seconds...]
   ENDIF
   IFVAR ROUNDTIME = 0
      EQUAL ROUNDTIME 4
      ADD ITEMVAL3 1
      IFVAR ITEMVAL3 = 1
         ECHO ALL You hear a muted squeaking sound. Apparently a family of mice has made its home in the counter's lower depths.
      ENDIF
      IFVAR ITEMVAL3 = 2
         ECHO ALL You hear a loud series of squeaks from within the counter.
      ENDIF
      IFVAR ITEMVAL3 = 3
         ECHO ALL You hear frightened squeaks from within the counter. The old man behind it looks up with a scowl on his face and says, "People keep kicking the counter today."
      ENDIF
      IFVAR ITEMVAL3 = 4
         ECHO ALL You hear a single, startled squeak from within the counter.
      ENDIF
      IFVAR ITEMVAL3 = 5
         ECHO ALL You hear an extremely loud squeak from within the counter.
         PLREVENT 1
         CONTPLREVENT
         ECHO ALL A little mouse climbs out onto the counter.
         PLREVENT 1
         CONTPLREVENT
         ECHO ALL The little mouse yells, "CUT IT OUT YOU DOPES!"
         PLREVENT 1
         CONTPLREVENT
         ECHO ALL The little mouse goes back down inside the counter, muttering angrily.
      ENDIF
      IFVAR ITEMVAL3 = 6
         ECHO ALL You hear a "ping"! The little mouse hurls a grenade out into the shop!
         DAMAGEALL SLASH 5 %N is cut by the shrapnel from the tiny grenade!
      ENDIF
      IFVAR ITEMVAL3 > 6
         ECHO PLAYER As you kick it you notice that the mice appear to have left in disgust.
      ENDIF
   ENDIF
ENDIF

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 4
The sign lists prices of the items that are for sale here.
*DESCRIPTION_END

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM READ 4
The sign reads...

                         ----- ----- ----- -----
                          Mr. Gaunt's Pawn Shop
                         ----- ----- ----- -----

        We buy almost anything! The following items are for sale:

               Necklace    $20
               Pendant      15
               Bracelet     10     Engagement ring    $300
               Ring         10     Wedding ring        175
               Brooch        5
               Earrings      5

  Free appraisals are avaiable. All transactions are FINAL. No exceptions
  made. Owner keeps loaded gun under counter. Consider yourself WARNED!

                                                            -- Management

*DESCRIPTION_END

STOREITEM 125 -1 10
STOREITEM 126 -1 5
STOREITEM 127 -1 5
STOREITEM 137 -1 15
STOREITEM 129 -1 20
STOREITEM 131 -1 10
STOREITEM 131 394 300
STOREITEM 131 395 175

IFPREVERB SELL -1
   CLEARVERB
   EQUAL DUMMY1 ITEMVAL1
   DIV DUMMY1 125
   STRCVT 0 DUMMY1
   IFVAR DUMMY1 = 0
      ECHO PLAYER The old man gives you a weird look and grumbles, "I have no interest in this! Stop wasting my time."
      ECHO OTHERS %N discusses some business with the old man behind the counter.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR DUMMY1 ! 0
      ECHO PLAYER The old man takes a look at %a. He gives you %0 dollars.
      ECHO OTHERS %N sells %a to the old man behind the counter.
      ADD WEALTH1 DUMMY1
      REMOVEITEM -1
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB APPRAISE -1
   CLEARVERB
   EQUAL DUMMY1 ITEMVAL1
   DIV DUMMY1 125
   STRCVT 0 DUMMY1
   IFVAR DUMMY1 = 0
      ECHO PLAYER The old man seems to show no interest in it.
      ECHO OTHERS %N discusses some business with the old man behind the counter.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR DUMMY1 ! 0
      ECHO PLAYER The old man says, "I'll give you %0 dollars, no more."
      ECHO OTHERS %N discusses some business with the old man behind the counter.
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB RECALL -1
   CLEARVERB
   ECHO PLAYER You seem to recall that the Pawn Shop used to be the Little Sew 'n' Sew.
ENDIF
